<rules>
INTRO (2-3 sentences, Ukrainian, plain text):
  - Start with a warm evening greeting ("Добрий вечір! 🌇" or similar)
  - Name the current day of week ({{ weekday_uk }})
  - In 1 sentence: name 2-3 key themes of today ("від ... до ...")
  - Natural, not salesy

ITEMS: Exactly 10 news articles from the provided list. For each:
  - emoji: one topic-fitting emoji (⚖️ for legal, ⛽ for fuel, 🏫 for schools, ☀️ for weather, etc.)
  - title: short sharp headline (5-10 Ukrainian words), rewritten shorter than original
  - hook: one-line teaser or question that intrigues the reader to click (3-8 words). Examples: "Португалії загрожує штраф", "Ресторани на межі вимирання", "Що буде далі?"
  - slug: exact slug from the provided list
  Order by importance/impact, most important first.
  If fewer than 10 news are provided, include all of them and repeat articles in importance order — but prefer to keep only news with type=news.

GLOSSARY: Exactly 2 Portuguese words that appear in today's articles, with Ukrainian translations.
  - Choose words that are practically useful for a Ukrainian immigrant (bureaucracy, everyday life, news vocabulary)
  - Format: short (1-2 words PT) — short (1-3 words UA)
  - Examples from user's preferred style:
    * acolhimento — прийняття
    * gratuito — безкоштовний
    * equivalência — визнання
    * imposto — податок

IMAGE_PROMPT (English, for gpt-image-1 high quality):
  - ONE photorealistic scene — Lisbon or Porto cityscape with real people, day or evening light
  - Weave elements from ALL 10 news stories into the environment:
    * prominent: billboards, newspapers being read, shop windows, street art (2-4 dominant stories)
    * subtle: background activities, pedestrian clothing, passing vehicles, graffiti (remaining stories as hints)
  - Atmospheric: warm golden hour, tram in background, azulejo tiles, pastel buildings
  - NO text overlays in the image itself (titles will be in the caption)
  - 120-200 words of English description
  - Specify "single coherent photograph, not a collage"
</rules>
